This document is an EDA notebook to explore descriptive and informative figures of the datasets incldued in the emidata package.

Data

We analyse three datasets:

  • ipapers2018_psydata (extracted data items related to psychology) has 107 records and 19 columns.
  • ipapers2018_csdata (extracted data items related to tech/cs) has 129 records and 21 columns.
  • ipapers2018 (list of analysed papers) has 136 records and 9 columns.

The final number of papers to analyse is 104.

Exploratory analysis of mental disorders (MDs)

Next exploratory tables and figures attempt to figure out whats going on. The initial assumption of the paper is that the field of mental disorder (md) drives the analysis. So we start exploring the related columns (variables), which are:

## [1] "md"      "md_mul"  "md_sub"  "md_id"   "md_desc"

How many distinct MDs are there?

There are 14 distinct MDs (out of 25). About 79.8% (N=83) are categorised according to Section II of DSM-5 manual. About 20.2% (N=21) are 23-Dual, 24-Multiple or 25-Suicidal behavior disorder/nonsuicidal self-injury.

Top3 MDs?

The top3 MDs are categorised in the DSM-5, and they all cover about 46.2% (N=48).

Variability of MDs over time?

Note: The period 2013-2017 covers full years. 2018 only covers the first two months (Bibliographic searches were conducted at the beginning of March 2018).

Remarks:

  • There is no clear temporal trend. Only that the last years attract more papers.
  • In terms of variaty, we can say that the range of MDs addressed by interventions.
  • Top3 mental disorders (4-Depressive disorders, 5-Anxiety disorders, 7-Trauma and stressor-related disorders) remain significant over all years.

Remarks:

  • There is a sharp peak in 2016-2017 compared to 2013-2015. Speculating a bit, it is plausible to say that the number of documents eligible for the years between 2008 and 2012 would have represented a small part of the total number of eligible documents, especially when compared with the last 5 years (2013-2018).
  • The 2015-2016 period accounts for (57.7%), while 2013-2015 accounts for (30.8%).
  • Only two months of 2018 (11.5%) almost reach the amount of documents in 2012 and 2013 together (14.4%).
